## Examples

Styling a parent element based on the presence of a child element: You can use the :has() pseudo-class to style a parent element based on the presence of a child element. For example, you can select all `<div>` elements that contain an `<h1>` element and apply a background color to them:
CSS

```css
div:has(h1) {
  background-color: #f2f2f2;
}
```

Styling an element based on the presence of a sibling element: You can use the :has() pseudo-class to style an element based on the presence of a sibling element. For example, you can select all `<p>` elements that immediately follow an `<h1>` element and apply a margin-bottom property to the `<h1>` element:

```css
h1:has(+ p) {
  margin-bottom: 0;
}
```

Styling an element based on the presence of multiple child elements: You can use the :has() pseudo-class to style an element based on the presence of multiple child elements. For example, you can select all `<div>` elements that contain both an `<h1>` and a `<p>` element and apply a border to them:
CSS

```css
div:has(h1 + p) {
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
}
```

Styling an element based on the presence of a specific child element: You can use the :has() pseudo-class to style an element based on the presence of a specific child element. For example, you can select all `<ul>` elements that contain an `<li>` element with a class of “active” and apply a background color to them:
CSS

```css
ul:has(li.active) {
  background-color: #f2f2f2;
}
```


